# README sync (pod-noir)

When a change affects **how people run, configure, or play** the project—or **how contributors build/test**—update **[README.md](README.md) in the same task** (same PR / session). Do not rely on the user to remember a docs pass.

## Update README when you touch

- **CLI**: `cmd/podnoir`, flags, subcommands, `internal/version`, new behavior users see in the terminal.
- **Session / game loop**: `internal/session` (REPL commands, shortcuts, solve mode, precinct policy, debrief, dossier).
- **Kube / scenarios**: `internal/kubectl`, `internal/scenario` (doctor, namespaces, safety/policy that players should know).
- **Ops**: `Makefile`, `docker-compose.yml`, `Dockerfile`, `.github/workflows/*`, config/env in `internal/config` or `POD_NOIR_*` usage.

## Sections to align (edit only what changed)

| Area | README sections |
|------|-----------------|
| Run paths | What you need, Quick start (Docker / native), kube-in-Docker note |
| Commands & flags | CLI reference table |
| REPL / solve | REPL shortcuts, solve-mode / precinct bullets |
| Env / integration | Environment (`POD_NOIR_*`) table |
| CI / dev | Development commands, CI (GitHub Actions), **[AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md)** if contributor paths change |

## Style

- Prefer **accurate, short** bullets and tables over long prose.
- Do not document every internal package or duplicate northstar doc; link **docs/pod-noir-northstar.md** for product intent when appropriate.
- If you add a **Makefile target** or **Compose service** that users or CI rely on, mention it in **Development** or **Quick start** as fits.

## If README is already correct

Say so briefly (e.g. “README unchanged—change is internal only”) and skip edits.

## Shipped work logging

For **feature / scenario / CI / policy** deliveries, also follow **[progress-sync](progress-sync.mdc)** and update **`PROGRESS.md`** + **`docs/progress/YYYY-MM.md`** (keep those files small; fan out detail by month).
